commit 6eeb531bee5e95dd191acee1ca5c1e4c62d5eb7a
Author: Mingsheng Xu <mxu61@ucsc.edu>
Date:   Wed May 8 15:10:35 2024 -0700

    Fix fetch target and restructure fetch target queue
    
    1. A fetch target (FT) is a sequence of consecutive instructions denoted by its start and end PC. It is always terminated by:
      - the icache line boundary
      - a taken cf
      - a fetch bar
      - the exit of the application
    
    2. The number of FTs the decoupled front-end can produce in a cycle is limited by the following two. The old `FE_BLOCKS_PER_CYCLE` is removed.
      - the maximum number of bytes that have been processed in a cycle, denoted by `FE_FTQ_BYTES_PER_CYCLE` (default 128)
      - the maximum number of taken branches that have been processed in a cycle, denoted by `FE_FTQ_TAKEN_CFS_PER_CYCLE` (default 2)
    
      If an FT has not yet been terminated by the time the decoupled front-end has reached the size limit, the FT will not be ready until the next cycle.
    
    3. The FTQ is restructured. Previously it was a flattened 1-d array, and now it is a 2-d array. The first dimension is for the FTs, and the second dimension is for the ops contained in a given FT. Interfaces are added/modified to incorporate the changes.

